{"parse":{"title":"spa","pageid":71723,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"spa\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Spa'''nish,es:e'''spa'''ñol}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|2&3|Spanish language|Spanish}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat|es}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|en|Spa}}\nThe term is derived from the name of the Belgian town of [[w:Spa, Belgium|Spa]], where since medieval times illnesses caused by iron deficiency were treated by drinking [[chalybeate]] (iron-bearing) spring water. In 16<sup>th</sup> century [[England]] the old Roman ideas of medicinal bathing were revived at towns like Bath, and in 1571 William Slingsby who had been to the Belgian town (which he called ''Spaw'') discovered a chalybeate spring in [[Yorkshire]]. He built an enclosed well at what became known as [[Harrogate]], the first resort in England for drinking medicinal waters, then in 1596 Dr. Timothy Bright called the resort ''The English Spaw'', beginning the use of the word ''Spa'' as a generic description rather than as the place name of the Belgian town. At first this term referred specifically to resorts for water drinking rather than bathing, but this distinction was gradually lost and many ''spas'' offer external remedies.\n\nThere are various stories about the origin of the name. A Belgian spring of iron-bearing water was called ''Espa'' from the {{der|en|wa|-}} term for \"fountain\", and was used in 1326 as a cure by an iron master with such success that he founded a health resort that developed into the town, though it has been suggested that this term may be derived from the name of the resort. Some have suggested that the town's name can be ultimately sourced from {{der|en|la|spargō|spargere|t=to scatter, sprinkle, or moisten}}, though this derivation is problematic.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈspɑː/|a=RP}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈspɔː/|a=UK,obsolete|ref={{R:Jespersen MEGoHP|I|10.571|303}}}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈspɑ/|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-spa.oga|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈspɐː/|a=AU}}\n** {{audio|en|En-au-spa.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈspa/|a=Scotland}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑː|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|spar|aa=non-rhotic}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A health [[resort]] near a mineral [[spring]] or [[hot spring]].\n# A [[trendy]] or [[fashionable]] resort.\n# A [[health club]].\n#: {{ux|en|They went to a '''spa''' for a massage.}}\n# A [[hot tub]].\n#: {{ux|en|Their bath is fitted  with a '''spa'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|Rhode Island|Massachusetts|Maine}} A [[convenience store]].\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|en|health club}}\n* {{l|en|resort}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|medispa|spa-goer|spalike|spathroom|spool||dental spa|spa cuisine|spagoer|health spa\n|Croft Spa\n|Boston Spa\n|Droitwich Spa\n|Leamington Spa\n|spa bath\n|spa pool\n|spa town\n|spa water|Woodhall Spa}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|health resort near a mineral spring or hot spring}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|llixhë|f}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|مُنْتَجَع|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|溫泉|tr=wēnquán}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|banejo}}, {{t|eo|banloko}}, {{t|eo|termoj|p}}, {{t|eo|varmobanejo}}, {{t|eo|termobanejo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kylpylä}}, {{t+|fi|spa}}\n* French: {{t|fr|ville d'eau|f}}, {{t+|fr|spa|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|სპა}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kurort|m}}, {{t+|de|Bad|n}}, {{t|de|Heilbad|n}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|סְפָּא|m|tr=spa}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|gyógyfürdő}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|termo}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|terme|f-p}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|温泉|tr=おんせん, onsen}}, {{t+|ja|スパ|tr=supa}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|ស្ប៉ា}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|aquae|f-p}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|spa|n}}, {{t+|pl|uzdrowisko|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|spa|m}}\n* Russian: {{qualifier|indeclinable}} {{t+|ru|спа|n}}, {{qualifier|Japanese style}} {{t+|ru|онсэ́н|m}}, {{t|ru|лече́бный исто́чник|m}}, {{t+|ru|ба́ня|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|spa|m}}, {{t+|es|balneario|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|hälsobrunn|c}}, {{t+|sv|spa|n}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|ılıca}}, {{t+|tr|kaplıca}}, {{t+|tr|kudret hamamı}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|ایلیجه|tr=ılıca}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|sba|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|trendy or fashionable resort}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Therme|f}}, {{t|de|Saunapark|m}}, {{t+|de|Spa|n|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{col|en\n|caldarium\n|pump room\n|sanatorium\n|take the waters\n|wellness hotel\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nShortened form of {{m|en|spastic}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/spɑː/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑː|s=1}}\n{{rfap|en|Ireland|variety=Ireland}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|Ireland|slang}} An idiot; a [[gobshite]]\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2010|author=Paul Murray|title=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8CI5XhzjSHEC&pg=PT808 Skippy Dies]|isbn=9780141943893\n|passage=What the fuck was she talking about, he must think she's such a '''spa'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|author=Rachael English|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5-9XEAAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|title=The Night of the Party\n|passage=['...] We'll say it was just the two of us sitting in the shed having a chat.'<br>'Don't be such a '''spa'''. Nobody will believe we were sitting in the shed having a chat.[...']}}\n# {{lb|en|Ireland|slang}} A clumsy person (see [[spastic]])\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993|author=Roddy Doyle|title=Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/paddyclarkehahah00rodd_0/page/17/|page=17|isbn=0-7493-9735-7\n|passage=— Hit it.<br>He missed.<br>— You're a big '''spa''', I told him.}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aps|APS|SAP|sap|APs|Psa.|PsA|s.ap.|asp|pas|Pas|PSA|ASP|PAs|PAS}}\n\n{{cln|en|heteronyms|terms derived from toponyms}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/spaː/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-spa.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|aː|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom earlier {{m|nl|spade}}, from {{inh|nl|dum|spade}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*spado}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*spadô}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nl|spade}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|m|spaden|+}}\n\n# [[spade]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom the ''Spa'' brand of mineral water, which originates from the Belgian town of {{m|fr|Spa}}. The compound {{m|nl|spawater}} is attested as early as the 17th century, however.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|m|-'s|+}}\n\n# [[mineral water]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|nl\n|spa blauw\n|spa rood\n}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{root|nl|ine-pro|*speh₁-}}\nFrom earlier {{m|nl|spade}}, from {{inh|nl|dum|spade}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*spādi}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*spēdiz}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|spät}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nl|spade}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{nl-adj|spader|spaadst}}\n\n# {{lb|nl|obsolete}} [[late]]\n#: {{syn|nl|laat}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{nl-decl-adj|spade|part=spaads}}\n\n{{cln|nl|genericized trademarks}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|nn|spada}}\n* {{alt|nn|spade}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom the noun {{l|nn|spade}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|no|/spɑː/}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|nn|verb|present tense|spar|past tense|spadde|past participle|spadd|or|spadt|present participle|spadande|imperative|spa}}\n\n# to use a spade or shovel, to [[dig]], to [[shovel]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n==Piedmontese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|pms|/spa/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|pms|noun|g=f|plural|spe}}\n\n# [[sword]]\n\n==Polish==\n{{wp|pl:[[+ (terapeutyka)|+]]}}\n[[File:Therme Vals outdoor pool, Vals, Graubünden, Switzerland - 20090809.jpg|thumb|spa]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|pl|SPA|SpA}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|pl|:ubor|en:spa|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|a=LL-Q809 (pol)-Olaf-spa.wav|hh=Spa}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{pl-noun|n|indecl=1}}\n\n# {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|beauty treatments designed to moisturise and nourish the skin; also: cosmetics used for such treatments}}\n# {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|health resort near a mineral spring or hot spring}}\n#: {{hyper|pl|bad|kurort|uzdrowisko|zdrojowisko}}\n# {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|hot tub}}\n#: {{syn|pl|jacuzzi}}\n#: {{hyper|pl|wanna}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{pl-adj|-|adv=-}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|postpositive}} {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|beauty treatments designed to moisturise and nourish the skin; also: cosmetics used for such treatments}}\n# {{lb|pl|postpositive}} {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|hot tub}}\n#: {{syn|pl|jacuzzi}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:WSJP|spa I|56636}}\n* {{R:pl:WSJP|spa II|91735}}\n* {{R:pl:PWN}}\n\n{{C|pl|Bathing|Cosmetics|Health|Places|Recreation}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ubor|pt|en|spa}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA}}\n* {{hyph|pt|spa}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|spa}} {{gloss|health resort near a spring}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pt:Aulete}}\n* {{R:pt:Priberam}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ubor|es|en|spa}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr|espá}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|spa}}\n#: {{syn|es|balneario}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n{{es-unadapted}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}\n\n{{cln|es|terms derived from toponyms}}\n\n==Swedish==\n{{wp|sv:}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom the name of the Belgian town of [[w:Spa, Belgium|Spa]]. {{etydate|1993}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sv-noun|n}}\n\n# {{l|en|spa}} {{gl|health resort with (hot) baths, and various treatments}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sv-noun-irreg-n|spa|[[spat]], [[spaet]]|span|spana|6=[[spats]], [[spaets]]}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|sv\n|spaanläggning\n|spaavdelning\n|spahotell\n|spaweekend\n|spabehandling\n}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:svenska.se}}"}}